        {
          "title": "What Are AI Agents? Core Concepts and Architecture",
          "slug": "what-are-ai-agents-core-concepts-architecture",
          "order_index": 0,
          "content": "# What Are AI Agents? Core Concepts and Architecture\n\nA single LLM call is like asking a very smart person a question and getting one answer back.\n\nAn **AI agent** is what you get when you wrap that same LLM in a *loop*: it can look at the world, decide what to do next, take actions (often via tools), remember what happened, and repeat until the job is done.\n\n![LLM-powered autonomous agent system overview (Weng, 2023)](/api/wiki-images/agent-fundamentals/images/lilianweng-posts-2023-06-23-agent_001.png)\n\n## Agent vs. “LLM pipeline”\n\nA useful mental split:\n\n- **Workflow / pipeline**: you (the developer) hard-code the steps: call model → parse → call search → call model → format.\n- **Agent**: you give the model a goal + tools + some rules, and it **chooses** which steps to run and in what order.\n\nThat “choosing” is the key: agents are dynamic. They can branch, recover from errors, and stop early when they’re done.\n\n## The core loop: perceive → plan → act → update\n\nMost agent systems reduce to four repeating phases:\n\n1. **Perception (observe)**: read the user request, tool outputs, files, web pages—anything that represents the current state.\n2. **Planning (think)**: decide the next step. Often this includes **task decomposition** (“what subgoals do I need?”) and sometimes exploring multiple candidate plans.\n3. **Execution (act)**: call a tool, run code, query a database, send an email—something that changes state or fetches missing info.\n4. **Memory update (learn/record)**: store what matters so the next loop is smarter (and so you don’t re-do work).\n\nA powerful pattern is to interleave reasoning and actions: reason a bit, take one concrete action, incorporate the result, then reason again. This tends to reduce hallucinations because the agent can “ground” itself in fresh evidence.\n\n## The three building blocks inside an LLM agent\n\n### 1) Planning\nPlanning is how an agent turns “do X” into a sequence of doable steps.\n\n- **Decomposition**: break a big task into subgoals.\n- **Search over thoughts**: instead of one linear chain, consider multiple candidate next steps and pick the best.\n- **Reflection**: critique previous attempts and revise the plan.\n\n### 2) Memory\nAgents need memory because real tasks don’t fit in one prompt.\n\n- **Short-term memory**: the current conversation/context window—your “working scratchpad.”\n- **Long-term memory**: external storage (often retrieval-based) so the agent can recall facts across sessions or long runs.\n\n### 3) Tool use (function/tool calling)\nTools are how agents stop being “just text.” With **function calling**, the model can output a structured request like: “call `schedule_meeting` with these arguments.” Your application executes it and returns the result.\n\nHere’s the shape of the loop in code-like form:\n\n```python\n# Pseudocode: the agent loop\nwhile not done:\n    msg = llm(prompt, tools=available_tools)\n    if msg.tool_call:\n        result = run_tool(msg.tool_call)\n        prompt = prompt + [msg, result]  # feed tool output back in\n    else:\n        done = True\n        return msg.text\n```\n\nThe important detail: tool calling is *multi-turn*. The model proposes an action; your system executes it; the model sees the output and decides what’s next.\n\n## A concrete picture: “LLM as orchestrator”\n\nSome systems push tool use further: the LLM doesn’t just call one tool—it routes work across many specialized tools/models (plan → select → execute → respond).\n\n![HuggingGPT: LLM orchestrates specialized models across four pipeline stages (Shen et al., 2023; image from Weng, 2023)](/api/wiki-images/agent-fundamentals/images/lilianweng-posts-2023-06-23-agent_010.png)\n\n## Summary\nAn **LLM agent** is an LLM embedded in a control loop that repeatedly observes, plans, acts via tools, and updates memory. Compared to fixed pipelines, agents are defined by **autonomous decision-making**: they choose the next step dynamically based on what they learn along the way.\n\n## Recommended Reading\n- [LLM Powered Autonomous Agents](https://lilianweng.github.io/posts/2023-06-23-agent/) — Clear breakdown of planning, memory, and tool use in agent architectures.\n- [Function calling (tool calling) guide](https://platform.openai.com/docs/guides/function-calling) — Practical, end-to-end flow for tool invocation loops.\n- [LangGraph agentic concepts](https://langchain-ai.github.io/langgraph/concepts/agentic_concepts/) — Crisp distinction between workflows and agents; patterns for orchestration.\n- [ReAct: Synergizing Reasoning and Acting in Language Models](https://arxiv.org/abs/2210.03629) — Why interleaving reasoning with actions improves reliability and interpretability.\n",
          "summary": "AI agents are LLMs wrapped in a loop that repeatedly observe, plan, act via tools, and update memory until a goal is achieved. The defining difference from a simple LLM call is autonomous control over which steps to take next.",
          "concepts": [
            "llm-powered agents",
            "agent architecture",
            "reasoning loop",
            "perception and action",
            "planning and task decomposition",
            "tool use and function calling",
            "short-term and long-term memory",
            "autonomous decision-making"
          ],
          "youtube_id": "zjkBMFhNj_g",
