          "title": "The ReAct Pattern: Synergizing Reasoning and Acting",
          "slug": "react-pattern-reasoning-and-acting",
          "order_index": 1,
          "content": "# The ReAct Pattern: Synergizing Reasoning and Acting\n\nIf you’ve ever watched an LLM “think step by step” and still confidently produce a wrong fact, you’ve seen the core limitation of pure **chain-of-thought reasoning**: it’s ungrounded. The model can build a beautiful internal story that never touches reality.\n\n**ReAct** fixes this by making “thinking” and “doing” take turns.\n\n![ReAct reasoning trajectories across knowledge and decision-making tasks. (Adapted from Lilian Weng; originally Yao et al.)](/api/wiki-images/agent-fundamentals/images/lilianweng-posts-2023-06-23-agent_002.png)\n\n## The big idea: don’t just reason—*interleave* reasoning with actions\n\nReAct stands for **Reasoning + Acting**. Instead of generating one long reasoning trace and then an answer, the model runs a loop:\n\n1. **Thought**: what do I know, what’s missing, what’s the next step?\n2. **Action**: call a tool (search, database, environment step, calculator, etc.)\n3. **Observation**: read the tool result and update the plan\n\nThis is the **thought–action–observation cycle**. It’s deceptively simple, but it changes the failure mode: when the model is uncertain, it can *ask the world* instead of guessing.\n\n## Why this helps: grounding and exception handling\n\nTwo common problems in “reason-only” prompting:\n\n- **Hallucination**: the model fills gaps with plausible-sounding facts.\n- **Error propagation**: one early wrong assumption poisons every later step.\n\nReAct adds a pressure-release valve: actions fetch real evidence (or real environment feedback), and observations let the model revise its plan mid-flight. The reasoning trace becomes a *living* plan, not a one-shot monologue.\n\n## A concrete mini-trajectory (QA with a search tool)\n\nImagine the question: “Which city is the birthplace of the author of *The Hobbit*?”\n\nA ReAct-style run might look like:\n\n```text\nThought: I need the author of The Hobbit, then their birthplace city.\nAction: search(\"The Hobbit author\")\nObservation: \"J. R. R. Tolkien wrote The Hobbit.\"\nThought: Now find Tolkien's birthplace city.\nAction: search(\"J. R. R. Tolkien birthplace\")\nObservation: \"Born in Bloemfontein, Orange Free State (now South Africa).\"\nThought: The city is Bloemfontein.\nFinal: Bloemfontein.\n```\n\nNotice what’s happening: the model isn’t “being smart” by memorizing everything—it’s being smart by **decomposing** the task and **grounding** each hop.\n\n## ReAct in practice: tool calling is the “Action” channel\n\nIn modern APIs, “Action” often means **function/tool calling**: the model emits a structured request, your app executes it, and you feed the output back as an observation.\n\nHere’s the mental model:\n\n- The model decides *when* to call a tool.\n- It produces *arguments* in a schema.\n- Your code runs the tool.\n- The result becomes the next-turn context.\n\nThis is exactly the ReAct loop, just implemented with structured messages instead of free-form text.\n\n## Design tips (what makes ReAct actually work)\n\n- Keep tools **narrow and reliable** (search, lookup, execute, step).\n- Make observations **verbatim** (don’t paraphrase tool output before the model sees it).\n- Encourage **small steps**: one action per missing piece of information.\n- Treat the reasoning trace as a **plan you’re allowed to edit**, not a proof you must defend.\n\n## Summary\n\nReAct is a simple but powerful pattern: interleave **reasoning traces** with **real actions** so the model can ground its beliefs in observations. The thought–action–observation loop reduces hallucination, supports task decomposition, and produces trajectories that are easier to debug and trust.\n\n## Recommended Reading\n- [ReAct: Synergizing Reasoning and Acting in Language Models](https://arxiv.org/abs/2210.03629) — The original paper introducing the pattern and showing why interleaving helps.\n- [LLM Powered Autonomous Agents](https://lilianweng.github.io/posts/2023-06-23-agent/) — A clear systems view of agents, where ReAct fits among planning, memory, and tools.\n- [Function calling guide (OpenAI)](https://platform.openai.com/docs/guides/function-calling) — Practical mechanics for implementing the “Action” step with tools.\n- [Function calling overview (Google Research)](https://goo.gle/4eEOLXR) — Another perspective on tool calling as a bridge from language to real operations.\n",
          "summary": "ReAct is an agent pattern where an LLM alternates between reasoning and tool-based actions, using observations to update its plan. This grounding via the thought–action–observation loop reduces hallucinations and makes multi-step problem solving more reliable and debuggable.",
          "concepts": [
            "react pattern",
            "thought-action-observation cycle",
            "chain-of-thought reasoning",
            "reasoning traces",
            "tool calling",
            "task decomposition",
            "grounded reasoning"
          ],
