        {
          "title": "Agent Planning: How Agents Decide What to Do Next",
          "slug": "agent-planning-how-agents-decide",
          "order_index": 2,
          "content": "# Agent Planning: How Agents Decide What to Do Next\n\nPlanning is the difference between an LLM that *answers* and an LLM that *does*. If you ask, “Write me a marketing plan,” a plain model can produce a nice document. But if you ask, “Launch a marketing campaign this week,” you’ve implicitly asked for a **sequence of actions**: research, draft, review, schedule, measure, iterate. That sequencing—plus the ability to change course when reality disagrees—is what we mean by **agent planning**.\n\n## Planning as a loop (not a document)\nA useful mental model is: **Goal → Plan → Act → Observe → Replan**.\n\n- **Goal**: what “done” looks like.\n- **Plan**: a proposed path (often a list of subgoals).\n- **Act**: take a step (maybe call a tool).\n- **Observe**: read tool outputs / environment feedback.\n- **Replan**: update the plan based on what you learned.\n\nThis is why agent frameworks emphasize *state* and *control flow*: the agent isn’t just generating text; it’s running a program whose next step depends on the last result.\n\n## Task decomposition: turning one big ask into small wins\nThe core planning move is **task decomposition**: break a big objective into smaller, checkable subgoals.\n\nA simple prompt can do it:\n\n```text\nGoal: \"Prepare a 30-minute lesson on backprop.\"\nList the subgoals in order. Make each subgoal testable.\n```\n\nGood subgoals are:\n- **small** enough to complete in one “burst” (one or a few tool calls)\n- **verifiable** (you can tell if it’s done)\n- **ordered** (dependencies are explicit)\n\n### Linear vs branching plans\n**Chain-of-thought** style planning is *linear*: step 1, then step 2, then step 3. That’s great when the path is obvious.\n\nBut some problems have forks: multiple plausible approaches, uncertain assumptions, or creative search. **Tree-of-Thoughts** style planning explicitly explores branches and then selects a promising path.\n\n![Tree of Thoughts explores branching reasoning paths beyond linear CoT. (Adapted from Lilian Weng)](/api/wiki-images/agent-fundamentals/images/lilianweng-posts-2023-03-15-prompt-engineering_002.png)\n\nIn agent terms: linear planning is “make a plan and execute,” while branching planning is “generate candidates, evaluate, pick, continue.”\n\n## Plan execution: the plan is a hypothesis\nA plan is not a contract—it’s a hypothesis about the world. Execution is where plans meet friction:\n- the API returns an error\n- the webpage layout changed\n- the data is missing\n- the user clarifies constraints mid-run\n\nSo robust agents treat each step as: **(a) choose an action, (b) run it, (c) interpret the result, (d) update state**.\n\nA common pattern is to interleave reasoning and acting (think: “decide → do → reflect → decide”). This reduces hallucination because the agent can *ground* its next step in real observations.\n\n## Feedback-driven replanning: when the world says “no”\nReplanning is triggered by **feedback**:\n- explicit failure (tool error, invalid output)\n- low confidence / inconsistency\n- new information that changes priorities\n\nA practical replanning prompt is short and surgical:\n\n```text\nWe attempted step 3 (\"fetch competitor pricing\") and got: 403 Forbidden.\nUpdate the plan. Keep completed steps fixed. Propose the next best action.\n```\n\nNotice the constraint: *don’t rewrite history*. Agents that constantly rewrite the whole plan can thrash; agents that never revise get stuck.\n\n## Orchestrating plans in code (a tiny graph)\nIn real systems, planning often becomes explicit control flow: nodes for “plan,” “act,” “check,” and conditional edges for “retry / revise / finish.”\n\n```python\n# Pseudocode-ish: the shape matters more than the library.\n\ndef plan(state):\n    return {\"todo\": [\"search\", \"draft\", \"review\"]}\n\ndef act(state):\n    step = state[\"todo\"][0]\n    result = run_tool(step)\n    return {\"last_result\": result}\n\ndef should_replan(state):\n    return \"error\" in state[\"last_result\"]\n```\n\nThis is the bridge from “LLM as a writer” to “LLM as a controller”: planning becomes something you can debug, trace, and improve.\n\n## Summary\nAgent planning is best understood as a loop: decompose a goal into subgoals, execute steps against the environment, and replan when feedback contradicts the current path. The most capable agents don’t just think step-by-step—they treat plans as hypotheses and stay responsive to what tools and the world actually return.\n\n## Recommended Reading\n- [LLM Powered Autonomous Agents](https://lilianweng.github.io/posts/2023-06-23-agent/) — Clear overview of planning, memory, and tool use in agent systems.\n- [Chain-of-Thought Prompting Elicits Reasoning in Large Language Models](https://arxiv.org/abs/2201.11903) — Why “think step by step” helps with multi-step decomposition.\n- [ReAct: Synergizing Reasoning and Acting in Language Models](https://arxiv.org/abs/2210.03629) — Interleaving actions with reasoning to reduce hallucination and handle exceptions.\n- [LangGraph Agentic Concepts](https://langchain-ai.github.io/langgraph/concepts/agentic_concepts/) — Practical patterns for implementing planning/execution loops with state and control flow.\n",
          "summary": "LLM agent planning is a goal-directed loop: break the task into subgoals, execute actions, observe feedback, and revise the plan when reality disagrees. Strong agents treat plans as flexible hypotheses and use environment signals to stay grounded and adaptive.",
          "concepts": [
            "llm agent planning",
            "task decomposition",
            "subgoal generation",
            "plan execution",
            "feedback-driven replanning",
            "multi-step reasoning",
            "goal-directed behavior"
          ],
          "youtube_id": "zjkBMFhNj_g",
          "video_title": "Intro to Large Language Models",
