        {
          "title": "Agent Memory: Short-Term Context and Long-Term Storage",
          "slug": "agent-memory-short-term-long-term",
          "order_index": 0,
          "content": "# Agent Memory: Short-Term Context and Long-Term Storage\n\nLLMs are *stateless*: every model call starts fresh, as if it just woke up. If you want an **agent** to feel coherent across multiple steps (and especially across multiple sessions), you have to build memory *around* the model.\n\nA useful mental model is: the model is the “brain,” and memory is the “notebook system” you keep handing it.\n\n![Human memory taxonomy mapped to LLM agent memory components (adapted from Weng, 2023).](/api/wiki-images/agent-memory/images/lilianweng-posts-2023-06-23-agent_008.png)\n\n## 1) Short-term memory = what’s in the context window\n\n**Short-term memory** (often called **in-context memory**) is the information you include in the prompt *right now*: the system instructions, the recent conversation, tool outputs, and any intermediate artifacts.\n\nIn many agent frameworks, this is represented as **conversation history** plus extra state (files, retrieved docs, partial plans). The key property is **thread scope**: it’s tied to one ongoing session.\n\nWhy it matters:\n- It keeps the agent consistent across multi-step tool calls (“we already tried endpoint A; now try B”).\n- It enables “working memory” behaviors like step-by-step reasoning and iterative refinement.\n\nWhy it breaks down:\n- Context windows are finite; long threads can overflow.\n- Even before overflow, models can degrade over long contexts (stale details distract, latency/cost rises).\n\nSo short-term memory often needs *management*: trimming, summarizing, or selectively keeping only what’s still relevant.\n\n## 2) Long-term memory = persistent storage you can retrieve later\n\n**Long-term memory** is anything stored outside the prompt that can be recalled later—across sessions, and even across different conversation threads.\n\nThink of it as a database of “things worth remembering,” such as:\n- User preferences (“prefers concise answers, uses vim keybindings”)\n- Stable facts (“project uses Postgres, not MySQL”)\n- Past outcomes (“the last deploy failed due to missing env var X”)\n\nThe key property is **retrieval**: you don’t paste the whole database into the prompt. You *search* it (often semantically via embeddings) and inject only the top relevant memories into the current context.\n\nThis is the core trick behind many memory systems: **store a lot, retrieve a little**.\n\n## 3) How they work together (the practical loop)\n\nA common agent loop looks like:\n1. Read current thread state (short-term).\n2. Retrieve relevant long-term memories for this user/task.\n3. Build the prompt with: instructions + recent messages + retrieved memories.\n4. Generate an action/response.\n5. Update short-term state; optionally write new long-term memories.\n\nHere’s a minimal sketch:\n\n```python\ndef agent_step(user_msg, thread_state, memory_store, user_id):\n    # 1) retrieve long-term memories\n    memories = memory_store.search(query=user_msg, user_id=user_id, limit=3)\n\n    # 2) build short-term context\n    messages = []\n    messages.append({\"role\": \"system\", \"content\": \"You are a helpful assistant.\"})\n    messages += thread_state[\"messages\"]  # recent conversation\n\n    # 3) inject retrieved memories into the prompt\n    mem_text = \"\\n\".join(f\"- {m['memory']}\" for m in memories)\n    messages.append({\"role\": \"system\", \"content\": f\"Relevant user memories:\\n{mem_text}\"})\n\n    # 4) call the model\n    assistant_msg = llm(messages)\n\n    # 5) update short-term + optionally write long-term\n    thread_state[\"messages\"].append({\"role\": \"user\", \"content\": user_msg})\n    thread_state[\"messages\"].append({\"role\": \"assistant\", \"content\": assistant_msg})\n    memory_store.add(thread_state[\"messages\"], user_id=user_id)  # optional\n\n    return assistant_msg, thread_state\n```\n\n## 4) A quick comparison\n\n| Property | Short-term (in-context) | Long-term (persistent) |\n|---|---|---|\n| Scope | one thread/session | cross-session, cross-thread |\n| Storage | prompt / agent state | external store (DB/vector store) |\n| Size limit | bounded by context window | effectively unbounded |\n| Access pattern | always included | retrieved on demand |\n| Typical use | coherence within a task | personalization + durable knowledge |\n\n*Table informed by common agent memory patterns described in LangGraph and agent memory writeups.*\n\n## Summary\n\nShort-term memory is the *working context* you pass into the model each step; it’s essential for coherence but limited and fragile at long lengths. Long-term memory is *persistent storage* you selectively retrieve into context, letting agents remember preferences and facts across sessions without stuffing everything into the prompt.\n\n## Recommended Reading\n- [Memory in LangGraph](https://langchain-ai.github.io/langgraph/concepts/memory/) — Clear breakdown of thread-scoped (short-term) vs namespace-scoped (long-term) memory.\n- [LLM Powered Autonomous Agents](https://lilianweng.github.io/posts/2023-06-23-agent/) — Intuitive agent architecture overview, including memory and retrieval.\n- [Mem0 repository](https://github.com/mem0ai/mem0) — Practical example of a long-term memory layer with retrieval + write-back.\n- [Retrieval-Augmented Generation for Knowledge-Intensive NLP Tasks](https://arxiv.org/abs/2005.11401) — Foundational idea: augment generation with retrieved external memory.\n",
          "summary": "Agent memory comes in two layers: short-term in-context state for coherence within a session, and long-term persistent storage that’s retrieved on demand to carry preferences and knowledge across sessions. Effective agents “store a lot, retrieve a little,” keeping prompts small while staying consistent over time.",
          "concepts": [
            "short-term memory",
            "in-context memory",
            "long-term memory",
            "persistent storage",
            "memory retrieval",
            "conversation history",
            "stateful agents"
          ],
          "youtube_id": "Mi5wOpAgixw",
          "video_title": "Multi-Agent Systems with LangGraph",
          "vimeo_url": null,
          "transcript": null
        },
        {
          "title": "Tool Use and Function Calling in Agents",
          "slug": "tool-use-function-calling-agents",
          "order_index": 1,
          "content": "# Tool Use and Function Calling in Agents\n\nA language model is great at *talking about* the world. An **agent** is what you get when you let the model *touch* the world—by giving it **tools**.\n\n![LLM-powered autonomous agent system overview (Weng, 2023)](/api/wiki-images/function-calling/images/lilianweng-posts-2023-06-23-agent_001.png)\n\n## Why tools exist (and why “just prompt it” isn’t enough)\n\nModels have two hard limits:\n\n1. They don’t automatically have fresh or private information.\n2. They’re not guaranteed to do exact computation or take real actions.\n\n**Function calling** (also called **tool calling**) is the bridge: the model can decide *when* to call a function and *what arguments* to pass, and your application executes the real code.\n\nTypical tool use cases fall into three buckets:\n- **Augment knowledge**: query a database, search, fetch a user’s account info.\n- **Extend capabilities**: calculators, code execution, charting.\n- **Take actions**: send email, schedule meetings, create tickets.\n\n## The core loop: plan → act → observe\n\nTool use is not a one-shot trick; it’s a loop.\n\n1. **You send** the user request + a menu of available tools.\n2. **The model replies** with either normal text *or* a **tool call** (function name + JSON arguments).\n3. **Your app executes** the tool.\n4. **You send back** the tool result as a **tool output**.\n5. The model continues—maybe answering the user, maybe calling another tool.\n\nThis is the agent’s **action space**: the set of things it is allowed to do (the tools you expose).\n\n## Defining a tool: name, description, and a schema\n\nA tool definition is basically a contract:\n- **name**: stable identifier (e.g. `schedule_meeting`)\n- **description**: helps the model choose correctly\n- **parameters**: a JSON schema describing the arguments\n\nGood schemas reduce “API hallucinations” because the model has less room to invent fields.\n\n## Invoking tools: an end-to-end minimal example\n\nBelow is the essential pattern: define tools → ask model → if it requests a tool, run it → feed result back.\n\n```python\nfrom openai import OpenAI\nimport json\n\nclient = OpenAI()\n\ntools = [\n  {\n    \"type\": \"function\",\n    \"name\": \"get_horoscope\",\n    \"description\": \"Get today's horoscope for an astrological sign.\",\n    \"parameters\": {\n      \"type\": \"object\",\n      \"properties\": {\n        \"sign\": {\"type\": \"string\", \"description\": \"e.g. Aquarius\"}\n      },\n      \"required\": [\"sign\"]\n    }\n  }\n]\n\ndef get_horoscope(sign: str) -> str:\n  return f\"{sign}: Next Tuesday you will befriend a baby otter.\"\n\n# 1) Ask the model, giving it the tool menu\nresp = client.responses.create(\n  model=\"gpt-5\",\n  input=[{\"role\": \"user\", \"content\": \"What is my horoscope? I am an Aquarius.\"}],\n  tools=tools,\n)\n\n# 2) If the model asks to call a tool, execute it\n# (Exact field names vary by SDK/model; conceptually you extract name + args.)\ncall = resp.output[0]  # pretend this is the tool call object\nargs = json.loads(call.arguments)\nresult = get_horoscope(**args)\n\n# 3) Send tool output back so the model can finish\nfinal = client.responses.create(\n  model=\"gpt-5\",\n  input=[\n    {\"role\": \"user\", \"content\": \"What is my horoscope? I am an Aquarius.\"},\n    {\"role\": \"tool\", \"name\": call.name, \"content\": result},\n  ],\n  tools=tools,\n)\n\nprint(final.output_text)\n```\n\nThe key idea: the model doesn’t *pretend* it queried something—it explicitly requests the query, and your system provides the ground truth.\n\n## Handling tool results (the part that makes agents reliable)\n\nTool results are just new evidence. Two practical rules:\n\n- **Always feed the raw result back** (even if it’s ugly JSON). Let the model format it for the user.\n- **Treat tool errors as first-class outputs**. If an API fails, return an error payload; the model can retry, ask a clarifying question, or choose a different tool.\n\nWhen you have many tools or frequently changing APIs, reliability improves if the agent can retrieve up-to-date tool docs or load tools on demand—otherwise models tend to guess argument names.\n\n## Standardizing tool integration (when your tool ecosystem grows)\n\nOnce you connect lots of external systems, you’ll want a consistent way to expose tools and context across apps. Protocols like **MCP (Model Context Protocol)** aim to standardize that “tool server” interface so models can plug into many data sources without bespoke glue code each time.\n\n## Summary\n\nFunction calling turns an LLM from a text generator into a controller that can *select actions* from a tool menu, pass structured arguments, and incorporate real-world results back into its loop. The reliability of an agent often comes down to careful tool schemas and disciplined handling of tool outputs and errors.\n\n## Recommended Reading\n- [Function calling guide](https://platform.openai.com/docs/guides/function-calling) — Practical, end-to-end patterns for defining tools, executing calls, and returning outputs.\n- [LLM Powered Autonomous Agents](https://lilianweng.github.io/posts/2023-06-23-agent/) — How tool use fits into the broader plan/act/observe agent architecture.\n- [Gorilla: Large Language Model Connected with Massive APIs](https://arxiv.org/abs/2305.15334) — Why accurate argument generation is hard and how retrieval helps.\n- [Model Context Protocol (MCP)](https://github.com/modelcontextprotocol) — A standardized way to connect LLM apps to external tools and data sources.\n",
          "summary": "Function calling lets an agent choose and invoke external tools using structured arguments, then use the returned results to continue reasoning in a plan → act → observe loop. Well-designed schemas and robust tool-output handling are what make tool-using agents dependable rather than guessy.",
          "concepts": [
            "tool use",
            "function calling",
            "tool definition",
            "tool invocation",
            "action space",
            "external api integration",
            "tool result handling"
          ],
