        {
          "title": "Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG) Inside Agents",
          "slug": "retrieval-augmented-generation-inside-agents",
          "order_index": 2,
          "content": "# Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG) Inside Agents\n\nA language model is a brilliant autocomplete engine. That’s also the problem: if it *can* produce a plausible sentence, it often will—even when it’s missing the underlying facts. **Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG)** is the engineering move that gives an agent a “library card”: before it speaks, it goes and fetches relevant pages.\n\n![LLM-powered autonomous agent system overview (memory + planning + tools). (Adapted from Weng)](/api/wiki-images/agent-memory/images/lilianweng-posts-2023-06-23-agent_001.png)\n\n## Where RAG sits in an agent loop\nAn **agent** isn’t just “LLM → answer”. It’s usually a loop:\n1) plan what to do, 2) call tools, 3) observe results, 4) update state, 5) respond.\n\nRAG is typically the “call tools” step for *knowledge*: the agent queries a knowledge base (docs, tickets, wiki, code) and injects the results into the next model call. This turns the LLM from “guess from weights” into **grounded generation**: “answer using these retrieved snippets.”\n\n## The core RAG pipeline (in one breath)\nRAG has two phases:\n\n**Indexing (offline / background)**\n- **Document chunking**: split long docs into chunks (often a few hundred tokens) so retrieval can be precise.\n- **Embedding**: convert each chunk into a vector (a point in semantic space).\n- **Vector index**: store vectors + metadata in a vector database.\n\n**Retrieval + generation (online / per question)**\n- Embed the user query.\n- Run **vector search** to get top-*k* similar chunks.\n- **Context injection**: put those chunks into the prompt.\n- Generate an answer constrained by that context.\n\n## Why embeddings make retrieval “semantic”\nAn **embedding** is a compact numeric representation where “similar meaning → nearby vectors.” That’s why a query like “reset my password” can retrieve a chunk titled “Account credential recovery” even if the words don’t match exactly.\n\nIn practice, retrieval quality depends on:\n- chunk size/overlap (too big = noisy, too small = missing context)\n- top-*k* (too low = miss facts, too high = distract the model)\n- metadata filters (e.g., product=“iOS”, policy_version=“2026-03”)\n\n## Retrieval strategies agents actually use\nAgents rarely do just one retrieval call.\n\n- **Single-shot retrieval**: simplest; good for direct Q&A.\n- **Multi-hop retrieval**: retrieve, read, form a better query, retrieve again (useful when the first hit is vague).\n- **Memory retrieval**: treat past interactions as a knowledge base (long-term memory) and retrieve relevant “memories” alongside docs.\n\nThe key agent insight: retrieval is not a one-time prelude—it’s a tool the planner can invoke whenever it notices uncertainty.\n\n## Minimal “RAG inside an agent step” (pseudo-code)\n```python\ndef rag_step(user_query, state):\n    q_vec = embed(user_query)\n\n    # semantic search over chunk embeddings\n    hits = vector_db.search(q_vec, top_k=5, filters={\"product\": state.product})\n    context = \"\\n\\n\".join(h.text for h in hits)\n\n    prompt = f\"\"\"\nYou are an agent. Use ONLY the context to answer.\nIf the context is insufficient, say what is missing.\n\nContext:\n{context}\n\nQuestion:\n{user_query}\n\"\"\"\n\n    answer = llm(prompt)\n    state.last_retrieved = hits\n    return answer, state\n```\n\nNotice two “agentic” touches:\n- the model is instructed to admit missing info (reduces confident hallucinations)\n- retrieved chunks are stored in state for later steps (citations, follow-up, auditing)\n\n## Summary\nRAG inside agents is simply: *retrieve first, then think and speak with receipts*. Embedding-based vector search makes retrieval semantic, and agent loops turn retrieval into an on-demand tool—called once, repeatedly, or even over the agent’s own long-term memory.\n\n## Recommended Reading\n- [Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG)](https://www.pinecone.io/learn/retrieval-augmented-generation/) — Clear motivation: hallucinations, cutoffs, and why retrieval helps.\n- [Retrieval-Augmented Generation for Knowledge-Intensive NLP Tasks](https://arxiv.org/abs/2005.11401) — The classic formulation combining parametric and non-parametric memory.\n- [A Comprehensive Guide for Building RAG-based LLM Applications (Part 1)](https://www.anyscale.com/blog/a-comprehensive-guide-for-building-rag-based-llm-applications-part-1) — Practical pipeline details: chunk → embed → index → retrieve → generate.\n- [LLM Powered Autonomous Agents](https://lilianweng.github.io/posts/2023-06-23-agent/) — How retrieval and memory fit into agent planning and tool use.\n",
          "summary": "RAG gives agents a reliable way to access up-to-date or private knowledge by retrieving relevant document chunks via embedding-based vector search and injecting them into the model’s context. In agentic workflows, retrieval becomes a tool the planner can call repeatedly, enabling more grounded, auditable generation.",
          "concepts": [
            "retrieval-augmented generation",
            "vector search",
            "embedding-based retrieval",
            "document chunking",
            "context injection",
            "grounded generation",
            "agentic workflows",
            "long-term memory retrieval"
          ],
          "youtube_id": "zjkBMFhNj_g",
          "video_title": "Intro to Large Language Models",
          "vimeo_url": null,
          "transcript": null
        }
      ]
