    {
      "title": "Introduction to LangGraph: Graph-Based Agent Orchestration",
      "order_index": 2,
      "lessons": [
        {
          "title": "Why LangGraph? Graphs as Agent Control Flow",
          "slug": "why-langgraph-graphs-as-agent-control-flow",
          "order_index": 0,
          "content": "# Why LangGraph? Graphs as Agent Control Flow\n\nMost “agent frameworks” start life as a **loop**: call the LLM, maybe call a tool, feed results back, repeat until done. That works—until your agent needs to *branch*, *retry*, *pause for a human*, or *run for hours* without losing its place.\n\nLangGraph’s core idea is simple: treat an agent workflow as a **graph**. Not because graphs are trendy—but because graphs are the natural data structure for real control flow.\n\n![LLM agent architecture: planning, memory, and tool use components. (Weng, 2023; adapted)](/api/wiki-images/agent-fundamentals/images/lilianweng-posts-2023-06-23-agent_001.png)\n\n## The problem with “chains”\nA linear chain is great when the path is predetermined:\n\n1. Generate draft\n2. Critique\n3. Revise\n4. Publish\n\nBut agents rarely behave that cleanly. In practice you want things like:\n- If the draft fails a check, go back and revise.\n- If a tool errors, retry with a different query.\n- If confidence is low, ask a human.\n- If the task is long-running, resume after a crash.\n\nYou *can* code all of that in Python `while` loops and `if` statements. The issue is that the control flow becomes implicit and hard to observe, debug, or persist.\n\n## LangGraph’s three building blocks\nLangGraph makes the control flow explicit with three primitives:\n\n### 1) **State**\nA shared, typed “scratchpad” that moves through the graph. Nodes read from it and return updates.\n\nA common default is **MessagesState** (a running chat transcript), but you can define your own state shape.\n\n### 2) **Nodes**\nA node is just a function (often an LLM call, a tool call, or a router) that takes `state` and returns a partial update.\n\n### 3) **Edges**\nEdges define what can happen next:\n- **Normal edges**: always go from A → B\n- **Conditional edges**: choose the next node based on state\n- **Cycles**: allow loops (retry, reflect, plan/execute)\n\n## A tiny graph: “hello world”\nEven the simplest LangGraph program already shows the mental model: START → node → END.\n\n```python\nfrom langgraph.graph import StateGraph, MessagesState, START, END\n\ndef mock_llm(state: MessagesState):\n    return {\"messages\": [{\"role\": \"ai\", \"content\": \"hello world\"}]}\n\ngraph = StateGraph(MessagesState)\ngraph.add_node(mock_llm)\ngraph.add_edge(START, \"mock_llm\")\ngraph.add_edge(\"mock_llm\", END)\napp = graph.compile()\n\napp.invoke({\"messages\": [{\"role\": \"user\", \"content\": \"hi!\"}]})\n```\n\nThe win isn’t “hello world.” The win is that once your workflow is a graph, adding branching and loops is a first-class operation.\n\n## Why graphs fit agents (especially long-running ones)\n### Explicit control flow\nInstead of burying logic inside a monolithic agent loop, you can *see* the workflow: which steps exist, where it can branch, and where it can cycle.\n\n### Cycles are normal, not a hack\nMany agent patterns are inherently cyclic: plan → act → observe → revise. Graphs represent this directly.\n\n### Stateful workflows unlock production features\nOnce execution is “state transitions over a graph,” you can support:\n- **Durable execution** (resume from the last state after failures)\n- **Human-in-the-loop** (interrupt, inspect, edit state, continue)\n- **Memory** (short-term working state + long-term persistence)\n- **Debugging/observability** (trace which nodes ran and how state changed)\n\nThese aren’t add-ons—they fall out naturally from the graph + state model.\n\n## Summary\nLangGraph is useful when your agent stops being a straight line and starts looking like real software: branching, looping, pausing, and resuming. By making **state** and **control flow** explicit as a **graph**, you get workflows that are easier to extend, debug, and run reliably.\n\n## Recommended Reading\n- [LangGraph GitHub README](https://github.com/langchain-ai/langgraph) — High-level overview of LangGraph’s goals and production features.\n- [LangGraph Introduction Tutorial](https://langchain-ai.github.io/langgraph/tutorials/introduction/) — Minimal examples showing nodes, edges, and compilation.\n- [LangGraph Agentic Concepts](https://langchain-ai.github.io/langgraph/concepts/agentic_concepts/) — Patterns like conditional routing and multi-step workflows.\n- [LLM Powered Autonomous Agents](https://lilianweng.github.io/posts/2023-06-23-agent/) — Clear mental model for planning/memory/tool-use that graphs often orchestrate.\n",
          "summary": "LangGraph treats agent orchestration as an explicit graph of nodes and edges operating over shared state, which naturally supports branching, loops, and long-running execution. This graph-based control flow makes agents easier to extend, debug, and run reliably with features like persistence and human-in-the-loop interrupts.",
          "concepts": [
            "langgraph",
            "graph-based orchestration",
            "nodes and edges",
            "agent state",
            "control flow",
            "cyclic graphs",
            "stateful workflows"
          ],
          "youtube_id": "zjkBMFhNj_g",
          "video_title": "Intro to Large Language Models",
          "vimeo_url": null,
          "transcript": null
        },
        {
          "title": "LangGraph Core Concepts: State, Nodes, and Edges",
          "slug": "langgraph-core-concepts-state-nodes-edges",
          "order_index": 1,
          "content": "# LangGraph Core Concepts: State, Nodes, and Edges\n\nLangGraph is easiest to understand if you stop thinking “agent framework” and start thinking **state machine**.\n\nYou define:\n- a **State** object (the shared memory)\n- **nodes** (pure-ish functions that read state and return updates)\n- **edges** (the control flow: who runs next)\n\nThen you **compile** the graph into something you can `invoke()` like a program.\n\n## 1) The StateGraph mental model\n\nA **StateGraph** is a directed graph where *every step* looks like:\n\n1. Take the current **state**\n2. Run one **node**\n3. Merge the node’s returned updates back into state\n4. Follow an **edge** to pick the next node\n\nThis is why LangGraph feels “low-level”: you’re explicitly designing the control flow and the memory layout.\n\n## 2) Typed state schema: your agent’s memory contract\n\nLangGraph wants you to be explicit about what can exist in state. In Python, a common pattern is a `TypedDict`.\n\n```python\nfrom typing_extensions import TypedDict\n\nclass State(TypedDict):\n    topic: str\n    joke: str\n    improved_joke: str\n    final_joke: str\n```\n\nThis schema is more than documentation:\n- It forces you to name the “slots” your workflow depends on.\n- It makes node I/O predictable: nodes return *partial updates* like `{\"joke\": \"...\"}`.\n\nA very common prebuilt schema is **MessagesState**, which stores a chat transcript under `messages`.\n\n## 3) Node functions: compute + return a patch\n\nA **node** is just a callable. It receives the full state and returns a **dict of updates**.\n\n```python\ndef generate_joke(state: State):\n    msg = llm.invoke(f\"Write a short joke about {state['topic']}\")\n    return {\"joke\": msg.content}\n```\n\nKey idea: nodes don’t “mutate” state directly. They return a patch, and the runtime merges it.\n\nThat merge step is where **state reducers** come in: when multiple updates target the same key (common in branching/parallel patterns), reducers define how to combine them (e.g., append messages rather than overwrite). Even if you don’t use reducers on day one, it helps to know that “merge semantics” are a first-class concept.\n\n## 4) Edges: the control flow (including conditional routing)\n\nEdges connect nodes. There are two special markers:\n- **START**: entry point\n- **END**: termination\n\nA straight-line workflow is just edges:\n\n```python\nfrom langgraph.graph import StateGraph, START, END\n\ngraph = StateGraph(State)\n\ngraph.add_node(\"generate_joke\", generate_joke)\n\ngraph.add_edge(START, \"generate_joke\")\n\ngraph.add_edge(\"generate_joke\", END)\n```\n\nBut the real power is **conditional edges**: a node can “decide” where to go next.\n\n```python\ndef check_punchline(state: State):\n    if \"?\" in state[\"joke\"] or \"!\" in state[\"joke\"]:\n        return \"Pass\"\n    return \"Fail\"\n\nworkflow = StateGraph(State)\nworkflow.add_node(\"generate_joke\", generate_joke)\nworkflow.add_node(\"improve_joke\", improve_joke)\n\nworkflow.add_edge(START, \"generate_joke\")\nworkflow.add_conditional_edges(\n    \"generate_joke\",\n    check_punchline,\n    {\"Fail\": \"improve_joke\", \"Pass\": END},\n)\n```\n\nNotice what’s happening:\n- `check_punchline` doesn’t update state; it returns a **route label**.\n- The mapping `{label: destination}` turns that label into the next node.\n\nThis is the core “agentic” ingredient: the path isn’t fully predetermined.\n\n## 5) Compilation: turning your graph into a runnable program\n\nAfter you finish wiring nodes and edges, you **compile**:\n\n```python\ngraph = graph.compile()\nresult = graph.invoke({\"topic\": \"databases\"})\n```\n\nCompilation is where LangGraph finalizes the execution plan and produces a runnable object that can be invoked (and, in the broader ecosystem, traced/streamed/persisted).\n\n![LLM agent architecture: planning, memory, and tool use components. (Weng, 2023)](/api/wiki-images/agent-fundamentals/images/lilianweng-posts-2023-06-23-agent_001.png)\n\n## Summary\n\nLangGraph programs are graphs where **state** is the shared memory, **nodes** compute and return state updates, and **edges** define what runs next. Once you add **conditional edges**, your workflow becomes dynamic—able to route based on what’s in state—while still staying debuggable and explicit.\n\n## Recommended Reading\n\n- [LangGraph Introduction](https://langchain-ai.github.io/langgraph/tutorials/introduction/) — Minimal “hello world” showing StateGraph, START/END, compile, and invoke.\n- [LangGraph Agentic Concepts](https://langchain-ai.github.io/langgraph/concepts/agentic_concepts/) — Clear examples of nodes + conditional routing in a workflow.\n- [LangGraph GitHub README](https://github.com/langchain-ai/langgraph) — High-level positioning and why stateful orchestration matters.\n",
          "summary": "LangGraph defines agent behavior as a stateful directed graph: nodes read state and return partial updates, edges control execution order, and conditional edges enable dynamic routing. Compiling the graph turns this specification into a runnable program that passes and merges state between steps.",
          "concepts": [
            "stategraph",
            "typed state schema",
            "node functions",
            "edges",
            "conditional edges",
            "graph compilation",
            "message passing",
            "state reducers"
          ],
          "youtube_id": "zjkBMFhNj_g",
          "video_title": "Intro to Large Language Models",
          "vimeo_url": null,
          "transcript": null
        },
        {
          "title": "Building Your First LangGraph Agent",
          "slug": "building-first-langgraph-agent",
          "order_index": 2,
          "content": "# Building Your First LangGraph Agent\n\nAn “agent” is just a loop with a memory: the model reads the conversation so far, decides what to do next (answer vs. call a tool), and you keep feeding the results back until you’re done. **LangGraph** makes that loop explicit and debuggable by turning it into a graph: nodes are steps, edges are control flow, and **state** is the shared scratchpad.\n\n![LLM agent architecture: planning, memory, and tool use components. (Adapted from Weng, 2023)](/api/wiki-images/agent-fundamentals/images/lilianweng-posts-2023-06-23-agent_001.png)\n\n## 1) The mental model: state in, state out\n\nIn LangGraph, every node is a function:\n\n- Input: a **state** object (often includes `messages`)\n- Output: a **partial update** to that state\n\nLangGraph merges updates for you, so you can write small, single-purpose nodes.\n\nWe’ll use the built-in **MessagesState** (a dict-like state with a `messages` list).\n\n## 2) Define tools (what the agent can *do*)\n\nTool calling is a structured handshake: the model emits a tool name + JSON arguments; your code executes it; then you return the tool result back into the conversation.\n\nHere’s a tiny tool:\n\n```python\nfrom langchain_core.tools import tool\n\n@tool\ndef multiply(a: int, b: int) -> int:\n    \"\"\"Multiply two integers.\"\"\"\n    return a * b\n```\n\n## 3) Create the agent node (the “brain”)\n\nBind tools to a chat model so it’s allowed to request them.\n\n```python\nfrom langchain_anthropic import ChatAnthropic\n\nllm = ChatAnthropic(model=\"claude-sonnet-4-6\")\nllm_with_tools = llm.bind_tools([multiply])\n\ndef agent_node(state):\n    # Ask the model what to do next given the conversation so far.\n    msg = llm_with_tools.invoke(state[\"messages\"])\n    return {\"messages\": [msg]}\n```\n\nKey idea: the model’s response might be normal text *or* a tool call.\n\n## 4) Add a tool-execution node\n\nLangGraph provides a ready-made **ToolNode** that reads tool calls from the last AI message, executes them, and appends tool outputs as messages.\n\n```python\nfrom langgraph.prebuilt import ToolNode\n\ntool_node = ToolNode([multiply])\n```\n\n## 5) Route conditionally: answer vs. call tools\n\nWe’ll add a small router that inspects the last message. If the model requested tools, go to `tools`; otherwise, we’re done.\n\n```python\ndef should_continue(state):\n    last = state[\"messages\"][-1]\n    # Most LangChain chat messages expose tool calls here when present.\n    if getattr(last, \"tool_calls\", None):\n        return \"tools\"\n    return \"end\"\n```\n\n## 6) Wire the graph and compile\n\n```python\nfrom langgraph.graph import StateGraph, MessagesState, START, END\n\ngraph = StateGraph(MessagesState)\n\ngraph.add_node(\"agent\", agent_node)\ngraph.add_node(\"tools\", tool_node)\n\ngraph.add_edge(START, \"agent\")\n\ngraph.add_conditional_edges(\n    \"agent\",\n    should_continue,\n    {\n        \"tools\": \"tools\",\n        \"end\": END,\n    },\n)\n\n# After tools run, go back to the agent to decide next step.\ngraph.add_edge(\"tools\", \"agent\")\n\napp = graph.compile()\n```\n\nCompilation is where LangGraph turns your declarative wiring into an executable runtime.\n\n## 7) Invoke end-to-end\n\n```python\nresult = app.invoke({\n    \"messages\": [\n        {\"role\": \"user\", \"content\": \"What is 12 times 13?\"}\n    ]\n})\n\n# Final assistant message is typically the last one\nprint(result[\"messages\"][-1].content)\n```\n\nIf the model chooses to call `multiply`, you’ll see a tool message inserted, then a final natural-language answer.\n\n## Summary\n\nA LangGraph agent is a tool-calling loop expressed as a graph: an **agent node** proposes the next action, a **tool node** executes real code, and **conditional edges** decide whether to continue looping or stop. Once compiled, you can invoke it like a normal function—while keeping the control flow explicit and inspectable.\n\n## Recommended Reading\n\n- [LangGraph Introduction Tutorial](https://langchain-ai.github.io/langgraph/tutorials/introduction/) — Minimal “hello world” and the core graph primitives.\n- [LangGraph Agentic Concepts](https://langchain-ai.github.io/langgraph/concepts/agentic_concepts/) — Patterns for routing, tool use, and agent/workflow design.\n- [OpenAI Function Calling Guide](https://platform.openai.com/docs/guides/function-calling) — The canonical tool-calling handshake (call → execute → return → continue).\n- [LLM Powered Autonomous Agents](https://lilianweng.github.io/posts/2023-06-23-agent/) — Big-picture architecture: planning, memory, and tool use.\n",
          "summary": "This lesson builds a complete LangGraph agent: define message-based state, add an LLM node and a ToolNode, route with conditional edges, compile the graph, and invoke it end-to-end. The key insight is that “agent behavior” is just explicit control flow over a shared state.",
          "concepts": [
            "langgraph state",
            "messagesstate",
            "tool calling",
            "tool node",
            "conditional routing",
            "graph compilation",
            "agent loop",
            "langchain integration"
          ],
          "youtube_id": "zjkBMFhNj_g",
          "video_title": "Intro to Large Language Models",
          "vimeo_url": null,
          "transcript": null
        },
        {
          "title": "Persistence, Checkpointing, and Human-in-the-Loop",
          "slug": "persistence-checkpointing-human-in-the-loop",
          "order_index": 3,
          "content": "# Persistence, Checkpointing, and Human-in-the-Loop\n\nLong-running agents have an awkward property: they’re *alive* (they take many steps, call tools, wait on APIs)… but most code is written as if it’s *instant* (a single request/response). The moment you add “wait for approval”, “retry later”, or “resume tomorrow”, you need two superpowers:\n\n1) **Persistence**: the agent’s state survives process restarts.\n2) **Checkpointing**: you can restart from a known-good point, not from scratch.\n\nLangGraph bakes these into the runtime so “pause/resume” is a first-class feature rather than an afterthought.\n\n## The mental model: a graph + a state + a thread\n\nIn LangGraph, your workflow is a graph of nodes (steps). Each node reads the current **state**, does work, and returns a partial update.\n\nA **thread** is the unit of “one ongoing run/conversation.” Think of it like an email thread: many turns, one shared context. LangGraph treats **short-term memory** as *thread-scoped state*.\n\nThe key move: that state is written to durable storage via a **checkpointer**. So if your server dies mid-run, you don’t lose the agent’s place—you reload the latest checkpoint and continue.\n\n## What exactly gets checkpointed?\n\nA checkpoint is a snapshot of the graph’s execution at a moment in time:\n\n- the current **state** (often includes message history, retrieved docs, intermediate artifacts)\n- where you are in the graph (what node is next)\n- enough metadata to resume deterministically\n\nLangGraph updates short-term memory/state as the graph is invoked and as steps complete, and reads it at the start of each step. That “read at step start / write at step end” rhythm is what makes resuming feel natural.\n\n## Human-in-the-loop: turning “pause” into a feature\n\nOnce you can persist state, you can safely **interrupt** execution and hand control to a human:\n\n- **Approval workflows**: “Before sending an email / placing an order / merging a PR, ask a human.”\n- **Review & edit**: a human can inspect the state (draft text, tool outputs, plan) and modify it.\n- **Escalation**: if the agent is uncertain or detects risk, it can stop and request guidance.\n\nThe important design idea is that the human doesn’t need to “replay” the whole run. They just see the current state at the interruption point, make a change, and then the graph resumes from that checkpoint.\n\n## A tiny sketch: resumable threads + approval gate\n\nBelow is a simplified pattern (pseudocode-ish) showing the *shape* of a resumable, interruptible workflow:\n\n```python\nfrom langgraph.graph import StateGraph, MessagesState, START, END\n\n# Node 1: draft something\ndef draft(state: MessagesState):\n    # ... call model, produce a draft\n    return {\"messages\": state[\"messages\"] + [{\"role\": \"ai\", \"content\": \"DRAFT: ...\"}]}\n\n# Node 2: approval gate (human-in-the-loop)\ndef needs_approval(state: MessagesState):\n    # In a real app, you'd interrupt here and wait for a human decision.\n    # The key is: state is checkpointed, so you can resume later.\n    return state\n\n# Node 3: finalize/send\ndef finalize(state: MessagesState):\n    return {\"messages\": state[\"messages\"] + [{\"role\": \"ai\", \"content\": \"SENT.\"}]}\n\ngraph = StateGraph(MessagesState)\ngraph.add_node(\"draft\", draft)\ngraph.add_node(\"approve\", needs_approval)\ngraph.add_node(\"finalize\", finalize)\n\ngraph.add_edge(START, \"draft\")\ngraph.add_edge(\"draft\", \"approve\")\ngraph.add_edge(\"approve\", \"finalize\")\ngraph.add_edge(\"finalize\", END)\n\napp = graph.compile(\n    # In practice you provide a checkpointer here.\n    # That enables durable execution + thread resumption.\n)\n\n# Invoke with a thread id so the run is resumable.\n# app.invoke(input, config={\"configurable\": {\"thread_id\": \"t-123\"}})\n```\n\nEven without the full interrupt API shown, notice the architecture: the approval step is just another node. The “magic” is that the runtime can stop after `approve`, persist everything, and later continue into `finalize`.\n\n## Thread management: the practical payoff\n\nOnce you adopt threads + checkpoints, you unlock operationally nice behaviors:\n\n- **Retries without duplication**: resume after transient tool failures.\n- **Async workflows**: pause while waiting on external systems.\n- **Auditable trajectories**: you can inspect what happened at each step (especially when paired with tracing/observability).\n\nThis is also a security and safety lever: if your agent is exposed to untrusted text (web pages, emails), human review checkpoints can prevent “model did something risky because it read something malicious” from becoming a production incident.\n\n## Summary\n\nCheckpointing turns an agent run into a resumable computation: state is persisted step-by-step so failures and pauses don’t force a restart. With that foundation, human-in-the-loop becomes straightforward—interrupt at any node, let a person inspect/modify state, then resume the same thread.\n\n## Recommended Reading\n\n- [LangGraph](https://github.com/langchain-ai/langgraph) — Overview of durable execution and human-in-the-loop as core capabilities.\n- [LangGraph Memory Concepts](https://langchain-ai.github.io/langgraph/concepts/memory/) — Clear explanation of thread-scoped (short-term) memory and persistence via checkpoints.\n- [LangGraph Documentation Home](https://langchain-ai.github.io/langgraph/) — Quickstart and conceptual guides for building stateful graphs.\n- [Prompt injection explained](https://simonwillison.net/2023/May/2/prompt-injection/) — Why review/approval gates matter when agents consume untrusted text.\n",
          "summary": "LangGraph’s checkpointers persist thread-scoped state so agent workflows can pause, survive failures, and resume from the last completed step. That same mechanism makes human-in-the-loop patterns—approval, review, and intervention at any node—feel like a natural part of the graph.",
          "concepts": [
            "checkpointing",
            "state persistence",
            "durable execution",
            "human-in-the-loop",
            "workflow interruption",
            "thread management",
            "resumable agents",
            "approval workflows"
          ],
          "youtube_id": "Mi5wOpAgixw",
