    {
      "title": "Advanced Agent Patterns and Multi-Agent Systems",
      "order_index": 3,
      "lessons": [
        {
          "title": "Multi-Agent Architectures: Supervisors and Subgraphs",
          "slug": "multi-agent-architectures-supervisors-subgraphs",
          "order_index": 0,
          "content": "# Multi-Agent Architectures: Supervisors and Subgraphs\n\nA single agent can “think longer” (more tool calls, more intermediate steps) and often get better results—until it can’t. Context fills up, attention gets noisy, and performance can degrade. **Multi-agent architectures** are a practical way to scale test-time compute *without* forcing one agent to carry the entire world in its head.\n\n![LLM agent architecture: planning, memory, and tool use components. (Weng, 2023; adapted)](/api/wiki-images/agent-fundamentals/images/lilianweng-posts-2023-06-23-agent_001.png)\n\n## Why a supervisor pattern exists\n\nWhen you have multiple agents, you need an answer to: “Who decides what happens next?”\n\nA **supervisor agent** (also called a manager/router) is an agent whose main job is *orchestration*:\n\n- interpret the user goal\n- break it into **subtasks**\n- **delegate** each subtask to a specialist agent\n- merge results, resolve conflicts, and decide whether to iterate\n\nThink of the supervisor as the “control plane” and the specialists as the “data plane.” The supervisor doesn’t need to be the smartest at everything—it needs to be good at *routing and verification*.\n\n## Delegation as a first-class tool\n\nA clean mental model: an agent can treat *other agents as tools*.\n\nThat means delegation looks like a tool call: “Ask the math expert,” “Ask the web researcher,” “Ask the code writer.” This keeps the supervisor’s prompt simple and makes the system composable.\n\nHere’s a minimal sketch (framework-agnostic pseudocode):\n\n```python\n# Supervisor loop (conceptual)\nplan = supervisor.llm(\"Decompose the task into 3-5 subtasks with owners\")\n\nresults = {}\nfor subtask in plan.subtasks:\n    results[subtask.id] = call_agent(subtask.owner, subtask.instructions)\n\nfinal = supervisor.llm(\n    \"Synthesize results, check for gaps, and produce final answer\",\n    context=results,\n)\nreturn final\n```\n\nThe key is that the supervisor’s context stays *thin*: it holds the plan and summaries, not every raw intermediate artifact.\n\n## Subgraphs: turning “a team” into a reusable component\n\nOnce you’ve built a good multi-agent collaboration for a recurring job (say, “research → outline → draft → QA”), you don’t want to rebuild it every time.\n\nA **subgraph** is that collaboration packaged as a single callable unit:\n\n- internally: multiple nodes/agents, possibly parallel\n- externally: one input, one output (plus state)\n\nThis is how you scale systems: you build small, reliable teams, then compose them into bigger workflows.\n\n### Parallelism is the hidden superpower\n\nSubgraphs make parallel execution natural. For example, a “research subgraph” might spawn 5 researcher agents in parallel, each exploring a different query angle, then a synthesizer agent merges their findings.\n\nParallelism buys you:\n\n- lower latency (wall-clock time)\n- diversity of perspectives (less single-threaded failure)\n- less context rot per agent (each agent sees a smaller slice)\n\n## Supervisor vs. subgraph: how they fit together\n\n- The **supervisor** is a *policy*: decide what to do next.\n- The **subgraph** is a *module*: a reusable chunk of execution.\n\nIn practice, you often have a top-level supervisor that routes into subgraphs:\n\n- “Need citations?” → call `ResearchSubgraph`\n- “Need implementation?” → call `CodingSubgraph`\n- “Need safety/format checks?” → call `GuardrailsSubgraph`\n\nThis is orchestration as software architecture: small units, clear interfaces, and explicit state.\n\n## Summary\n\nMulti-agent systems let you scale test-time compute while keeping each agent’s context focused. A supervisor pattern provides dynamic routing and synthesis, while subgraphs package proven multi-agent collaborations into reusable building blocks that can run in parallel.\n\n## Recommended Reading\n\n- [LLM Powered Autonomous Agents](https://lilianweng.github.io/posts/2023-06-23-agent/) — Clear breakdown of planning, memory, and tool use that motivates delegation.\n- [OpenAI Agents SDK](https://openai.github.io/openai-agents-python/) — Lightweight primitives for handoffs (agents as tools) and guardrails.\n- [LangGraph Introduction](https://langchain-ai.github.io/langgraph/tutorials/introduction/) — Low-level orchestration with stateful graphs and durable execution.\n- [AutoGen (GitHub)](https://github.com/microsoft/autogen) — Practical multi-agent conversation patterns and orchestration examples.\n",
          "summary": "Supervisor patterns route and coordinate specialized agents, keeping any single agent’s context small while still scaling test-time compute. Subgraphs package multi-agent collaborations into reusable modules that can be composed and run in parallel.",
          "concepts": [
            "multi-agent systems",
            "supervisor agent",
            "agent delegation",
            "agents as tools",
            "subgraph composition",
            "parallel agent execution",
            "agent orchestration"
          ],
          "youtube_id": "Mi5wOpAgixw",
          "video_title": "Multi-agent systems (overview and ways to build them)",
          "vimeo_url": null,
          "transcript": null
