        {
          "title": "Implementing a ReAct Agent with LangGraph",
          "slug": "implementing-react-agent-langgraph",
          "order_index": 1,
          "content": "# Implementing a ReAct Agent with LangGraph\n\nA good agent isn’t “one big prompt.” It’s a **loop**: the model thinks, takes an action (often a tool call), observes what happened, and then updates its plan. The ReAct pattern is simply that loop made explicit.\n\nLangGraph is a great fit because it lets you draw that loop as a **graph**: nodes are steps (reason, act, observe), edges decide what happens next, and **state** is the shared scratchpad that persists across iterations.\n\n![LLM agent architecture: planning, memory, and tool use components. (Weng, 2023; adapted)](/api/wiki-images/agent-fundamentals/images/lilianweng-posts-2023-06-23-agent_001.png)\n\n## The ReAct loop, translated into a graph\n\nReAct alternates between:\n\n- **Reasoning**: decide what to do next (and whether a tool is needed)\n- **Acting**: call a tool with structured arguments\n- **Observation**: feed the tool result back into the model\n\nIn LangGraph, that becomes a cycle:\n\n`START → reason → (tools?) → observe → reason → … → END`\n\nThe key design choice: store the conversation as a list of **messages** in state, and keep appending new messages as the agent runs.\n\n## Minimal, working LangGraph ReAct agent (Python)\n\nBelow is a compact implementation that maps directly onto the loop. It uses:\n\n- a chat model that supports **tool calling**\n- a **tool node** that executes tool calls\n- a **router** that decides whether to continue looping\n\n```python\n# pip install -U langgraph langchain_core\n\nfrom typing import TypedDict, List, Any\nfrom langgraph.graph import StateGraph, START, END\n\n# If you're using LangChain chat models, messages are typically dict-like.\nMessage = dict\n\nclass AgentState(TypedDict):\n    messages: List[Message]\n\n# --- 1) Define tools (plain Python functions) ---\n\ndef multiply(a: int, b: int) -> int:\n    return a * b\n\nTOOLS = {\"multiply\": multiply}\n\n# --- 2) Reasoning node: ask the LLM what to do next ---\n\ndef reason(state: AgentState):\n    \"\"\"Call the model with the running message history.\n\n    The model may respond normally OR emit tool_calls.\n    \"\"\"\n    msg_history = state[\"messages\"]\n\n    # Pseudocode: replace with your model client.\n    # The important part is: the model sees tools and can return tool_calls.\n    ai_msg = llm_with_tools.invoke(msg_history)  # returns a message-like object\n\n    return {\"messages\": msg_history + [ai_msg]}\n\n# --- 3) Tool execution node: run requested tools and append observations ---\n\ndef act(state: AgentState):\n    last = state[\"messages\"][-1]\n    tool_calls = last.get(\"tool_calls\", [])\n\n    new_messages = list(state[\"messages\"])\n\n    for call in tool_calls:\n        name = call[\"name\"]\n        args = call.get(\"args\", {})\n\n        result = TOOLS[name](**args)\n\n        # Tool outputs are appended as messages so the LLM can \"observe\" them.\n        new_messages.append({\n            \"role\": \"tool\",\n            \"name\": name,\n            \"content\": str(result),\n            \"tool_call_id\": call.get(\"id\"),\n        })\n\n    return {\"messages\": new_messages}\n\n# --- 4) Router: decide whether to call tools or finish ---\n\ndef should_act(state: AgentState) -> str:\n    last = state[\"messages\"][-1]\n    if last.get(\"tool_calls\"):\n        return \"act\"\n    return \"end\"\n\n# --- 5) Build the graph ---\n\ng = StateGraph(AgentState)\n\ng.add_node(\"reason\", reason)\n\ng.add_node(\"act\", act)\n\ng.add_edge(START, \"reason\")\n\ng.add_conditional_edges(\"reason\", should_act, {\n    \"act\": \"act\",\n    \"end\": END,\n})\n\ng.add_edge(\"act\", \"reason\")  # observation → next reasoning step\n\ngraph = g.compile()\n\n# --- 6) Run it ---\n\nfinal = graph.invoke({\n    \"messages\": [\n        {\"role\": \"user\", \"content\": \"What is 12 times 7? Use tools.\"}\n    ]\n})\n\nprint(final[\"messages\"][-1][\"content\"])\n```\n\n### What to notice\n\n- The **only persistent memory** here is `state[\"messages\"]`. That’s enough to implement the ReAct loop.\n- The **reason** node doesn’t execute tools; it only *requests* them.\n- The **act** node is deterministic Python: it executes tool calls and appends **observations**.\n- The edge `act → reason` is the “O → T” part of the thought-action-observation cycle.\n\n## Practical tips (the stuff that saves hours)\n\n- **Make tool outputs explicit and structured** when possible. If the observation is ambiguous, the next reasoning step becomes guessy.\n- Add a **max-iterations** guard (e.g., a counter in state) to prevent infinite loops.\n- When debugging, log the message list each step. ReAct failures are usually “bad observation formatting” or “tool schema mismatch,” not mysterious model behavior.\n\n## Summary\n\nReAct is a simple idea: interleave reasoning with tool actions and feed observations back into the model. LangGraph makes this pattern concrete by turning the loop into a small graph where state (messages) flows through `reason → act → reason` until the model stops requesting tools.\n\n## Recommended Reading\n\n- [ReAct: Synergizing Reasoning and Acting in Language Models](https://arxiv.org/abs/2210.03629) — The original ReAct paper and motivation.\n- [LangGraph: Agentic concepts](https://langchain-ai.github.io/langgraph/concepts/agentic_concepts/) — How LangGraph thinks about agents, tools, and routing.\n- [LangGraph Introduction Tutorial](https://langchain-ai.github.io/langgraph/tutorials/introduction/) — The core graph API and mental model.\n- [OpenAI Function Calling Guide](https://platform.openai.com/docs/guides/function-calling) — The canonical “tool call → execute → return output → continue” flow.\n",
          "summary": "This lesson implements the ReAct thought-action-observation loop as a LangGraph cycle, using a reasoning node to request tool calls and a tool node to execute them and append observations back into state. The result is a minimal, debuggable agent loop that iterates until the model stops calling tools.",
          "concepts": [
            "react loop",
            "thought-action-observation",
            "langgraph state",
            "tool calling",
            "tool execution node",
            "conditional routing",
            "iterative agent execution"
          ],
          "youtube_id": "zjkBMFhNj_g",
          "video_title": "Intro to Large Language Models",
          "vimeo_url": null,
          "transcript": null
        },
        {
          "title": "Streaming, Debugging, and Observability in LangGraph",
          "slug": "streaming-debugging-observability-langgraph",
          "order_index": 2,
          "content": "# Streaming, Debugging, and Observability in LangGraph\n\nWhen you build an agent, you’re really building a *runtime*: something that thinks, calls tools, updates state, and sometimes runs for a long time. In that world, “it returned the right final answer” is not enough. You want three superpowers:\n\n1. **Streaming** so users see progress immediately.\n2. **Intermediate state inspection** so you can debug *why* the agent did what it did.\n3. **Observability** so production runs don’t become spooky black boxes.\n\n## 1) Streaming: make long runs feel fast\n\nLangGraph graphs can stream execution as they run. Conceptually, instead of waiting for `invoke()` to finish, you iterate over events.\n\nThere are two common “streams” you care about:\n\n- **Token streaming**: show partial model output as it’s generated.\n- **Step streaming**: show *graph progress* (node-by-node updates, tool calls, state changes).\n\nA minimal pattern looks like this:\n\n```python\nfrom langgraph.graph import StateGraph, MessagesState, START, END\n\n# A tiny node that appends an AI message\ndef mock_llm(state: MessagesState):\n    return {\"messages\": [{\"role\": \"ai\", \"content\": \"hello world\"}]}\n\nbuilder = StateGraph(MessagesState)\nbuilder.add_node(\"mock_llm\", mock_llm)\nbuilder.add_edge(START, \"mock_llm\")\nbuilder.add_edge(\"mock_llm\", END)\n\ngraph = builder.compile()\n\n# Pseudocode: stream events instead of waiting for invoke()\nfor event in graph.stream({\"messages\": [{\"role\": \"user\", \"content\": \"hi\"}]}):\n    print(event)\n```\n\nIn real apps, you typically map these events into UI updates:\n\n- If the event contains model tokens → append to the chat bubble.\n- If the event contains a tool call → show a “Calling tool…” status line.\n- If the event contains a state patch → update a debug panel.\n\nThe key mental model: **streaming is not just UX sugar**—it’s also your first debugging tool, because you can see *where time goes* and *what step you’re on*.\n\n## 2) Debugging by inspecting intermediate state\n\nLangGraph is stateful by design: each node reads some **state**, returns a **partial update**, and the runtime merges it into the global state.\n\nThat makes debugging pleasantly concrete:\n\n- If the agent “forgets” something, it’s usually a state update problem.\n- If the agent loops, it’s usually an edge/condition problem.\n- If the agent calls the wrong tool, it’s often a messages/history problem.\n\nA practical workflow:\n\n1. **Print or log state deltas** at each node (what changed?).\n2. **Inspect the message list** (what did the model actually see?).\n3. **Add a small gate node** that asserts invariants (e.g., “must have retrieved docs before answering”).\n\nBecause nodes are just Python functions, you can also do “boring” debugging that works:\n\n```python\ndef my_node(state):\n    # breakpoint()  # uncomment in local dev\n    assert \"messages\" in state\n    return {\"messages\": state[\"messages\"] + [{\"role\": \"ai\", \"content\": \"ok\"}]}\n```\n\nThis is the advantage of a low-level orchestration framework: you’re not fighting hidden control flow.\n\n## 3) Observability: tracing runs in LangSmith\n\nLocal debugging gets you to “works on my machine.” **Observability** gets you to “works on Tuesday at 3am.”\n\nIn practice, you want:\n\n- **Execution traces**: which nodes ran, in what order, with what inputs/outputs.\n- **State transitions**: how the state evolved over time.\n- **Runtime metrics**: latency, token usage, error rates.\n\nLangGraph integrates naturally with LangSmith tracing. The setup is intentionally simple: enable tracing via environment variables, then run your graph as usual.\n\n```bash\nexport LANGSMITH_TRACING=true\nexport LANGSMITH_API_KEY=...  # your key\n```\n\nOnce enabled, each run becomes a navigable trace: you can click through node executions, inspect intermediate artifacts, and compare “good” vs “bad” trajectories.\n\n### Production mindset: what to monitor\n\nA lightweight checklist that catches most real failures:\n\n- **Tool error rate** (timeouts, 4xx/5xx, parsing failures)\n- **Looping / max-iteration hits** (agent got stuck)\n- **Latency percentiles** (p50/p95/p99)\n- **Token spikes** (prompt bloat, runaway context)\n\nIf you can answer “what step did it fail on?” in one click, you’re already ahead.\n\n## Summary\n\nStreaming makes agents feel responsive and exposes progress in real time. Intermediate state inspection turns debugging into a state-diff exercise instead of guesswork. Observability (via tracing) is what lets you understand, measure, and trust agent behavior once it’s running in production.\n\n## Recommended Reading\n\n- [LangGraph GitHub README](https://github.com/langchain-ai/langgraph) — Overview of LangGraph’s core capabilities (streaming, durable execution, debugging).\n- [LangGraph Introduction Tutorial](https://langchain-ai.github.io/langgraph/tutorials/introduction/) — Minimal graphs, compilation, and invocation patterns.\n- [LangGraph Agentic Concepts](https://langchain-ai.github.io/langgraph/concepts/agentic_concepts/) — How state, nodes, and conditional routing fit together.\n- [Eugene Yan — LLM Patterns](https://eugeneyan.com/writing/llm-patterns/) — Production patterns and the “don’t fly blind” mindset for LLM systems.\n",
          "summary": "This lesson shows how to stream LangGraph executions for responsive UX, debug agents by inspecting intermediate state updates, and add observability with tracing so production behavior is explainable and measurable.",
          "concepts": [
            "agent streaming",
            "token streaming",
            "step streaming",
            "intermediate state inspection",
            "graph debugging",
            "execution tracing",
            "observability",
            "production monitoring"
          ],
          "youtube_id": "zjkBMFhNj_g",
          "video_title": "Intro to Large Language Models",
          "vimeo_url": null,
          "transcript": null
        }
