        {
          "title": "Real-World Agent Use Cases and Production Patterns",
          "slug": "real-world-agent-use-cases-production-patterns",
          "order_index": 2,
          "content": "# Real-World Agent Use Cases and Production Patterns\n\nA demo agent is easy: it answers a question, writes a snippet, maybe calls a tool once. A production agent is different: it has to be *predictable under stress*—bad inputs, flaky APIs, long conversations, adversarial users, and changing data.\n\nThe trick is to think of an agent as **a system**, not a model: the LLM is the “brain”, but reliability comes from the scaffolding around it.\n\n![LLM agent architecture: planning, memory, and tool use components. (Adapted from Weng, 2023)](/api/wiki-images/agent-fundamentals/images/lilianweng-posts-2023-06-23-agent_001.png)\n\n## Use case 1: Research assistant (RAG-first)\n\nA **research assistant agent** is usually a retrieval-and-synthesis machine: find relevant sources, quote them, and produce a grounded answer.\n\n**Production pattern:** make retrieval a first-class step.\n- Chunk → embed → index your docs.\n- At query time: embed query → retrieve top-*k* → (optionally) rerank → generate with citations.\n\nWhy this matters: base models are “stuck in the past” and will confidently fill gaps. RAG turns “I think” into “here’s what the docs say.”\n\n## Use case 2: Code generation agent (tools + verification)\n\nA **code generation agent** isn’t just “write code”—it’s “write code that compiles, passes tests, and matches repo conventions.”\n\n**Production pattern:** split generation from checking.\n1) Generate a patch.\n2) Run tools: formatter, type checker, unit tests.\n3) If failures: feed *only the error output* back and retry with constraints.\n\nThis turns the LLM from a one-shot author into a loop that converges.\n\n```python\n# Pseudocode: a minimal repair loop\nfor attempt in range(3):\n    patch = llm(\"Implement feature X. Output a git diff.\")\n    apply(patch)\n    ok, logs = run(\"pytest -q\")\n    if ok:\n        break\n    llm(f\"Tests failed. Here are logs:\\n{logs}\\nFix the diff.\")\n```\n\n## Use case 3: Customer support bot (workflow + guardrails)\n\nA **customer support automation** agent lives in a world of policies, authentication, and escalation paths.\n\n**Production pattern:** prefer *workflows* over “free-form autonomy.”\n- Collect required fields (order id, email, issue type).\n- Call tools (CRM lookup, refund API).\n- Enforce policy (refund limits, eligibility).\n- Escalate to a human when confidence is low or risk is high.\n\nThis is also where **prompt injection** becomes real: users (or retrieved text) can try to override instructions. Treat all external text as untrusted input.\n\n## Reliability patterns you’ll reuse everywhere\n\n### 1) Tool calling with schemas (reduce ambiguity)\n**Function/tool calling** forces the model to produce structured arguments instead of “API-ish prose.” Your app executes the tool, then the model explains results.\n\n### 2) Defensive UX (design for failure)\nAssume:\n- the model will be wrong sometimes,\n- tools will time out,\n- users will ask underspecified questions.\n\nSo build:\n- clarifying questions,\n- safe fallbacks (“Here’s what I can do next…”),\n- graceful degradation (answer without tool if tool is down).\n\n### 3) Error handling + retries (but with rules)\nRetries should be **bounded** and **typed**:\n- Retry network timeouts with backoff.\n- Don’t blindly retry invalid tool arguments—ask the model to repair.\n- Log every failure with enough context to reproduce.\n\n### 4) Evals in the loop (don’t fly blind)\nAgents regress easily: a prompt tweak, a new retriever, a model upgrade. **Evaluations** are your early-warning system—measure quality, latency, and cost on representative tasks, and run them continuously.\n\n## Summary\nProduction agents succeed when you treat the LLM as one component in a larger, testable system: retrieval for grounding, tools for action, workflows for control, and evals for stability. The “agent magic” is real—but reliability comes from engineering.\n\n## Recommended Reading\n- [Practical patterns for integrating LLMs into systems & products](https://eugeneyan.com/writing/llm-patterns/) — A clear map of evals, RAG, guardrails, defensive UX, and feedback loops.\n- [A comprehensive guide for building RAG-based LLM applications](https://www.anyscale.com/blog/a-comprehensive-guide-for-building-rag-based-llm-applications-part-1) — End-to-end RAG pipeline thinking, including scaling and evaluation.\n- [Function calling / tool calling guide](https://platform.openai.com/docs/guides/function-calling) — The canonical structured tool-calling flow.\n- [Prompt injection explained](https://simonwillison.net/2023/May/2/prompt-injection/) — Why “just add more prompt text” isn’t a security strategy.\n",
          "summary": "Real-world agents are best understood as systems: the LLM is the controller, but reliability comes from retrieval, tool schemas, workflows, retries, and continuous evals. Research, coding, and support agents each push you toward different production patterns, but they share the same core reliability playbook.",
          "concepts": [
            "production agent deployment",
            "research assistant agent",
            "code generation agent",
            "customer support automation",
            "tool calling and structured outputs",
            "error handling and retries",
            "agent reliability and evals"
          ],
          "youtube_id": "zjkBMFhNj_g",
          "video_title": "Intro to Large Language Models",
          "vimeo_url": null,
          "transcript": null
