        {
          "title": "Capstone: Designing and Building a Production-Ready Agent",
          "slug": "capstone-designing-building-production-ready-agent",
          "order_index": 3,
          "content": "# Capstone: Designing and Building a Production-Ready Agent\n\nDemos are easy: one prompt, one tool, one happy path. Products are the opposite: messy inputs, partial failures, long-running tasks, and users who *change their mind mid-flight*. This capstone is about building an agent that survives that reality.\n\nWe’ll design an end-to-end agent in **LangGraph** that can: remember, retrieve, act with tools, pause for human approval, and emit traces you can debug.\n\n## 1) Start with a “contract”: what does success look like?\n\nBefore code, write a one-paragraph spec:\n\n- **User goal**: e.g., “Answer questions about our internal handbook and optionally open a ticket.”\n- **Allowed actions**: search docs, read ticket status, create ticket.\n- **Non-goals**: no guessing policy; must cite sources when using docs.\n- **Failure mode**: if retrieval is weak or action is risky → ask a clarifying question or request approval.\n\nThis spec becomes your eval set later.\n\n## 2) Draw the agent as a graph (not a loop)\n\nLangGraph shines when you stop thinking “while True: call LLM” and start thinking **states and transitions**.\n\nA practical production graph:\n\n1. **Router**: decide “RAG answer” vs “tool action” vs “clarify”.\n2. **Retrieve**: embed query → fetch top-k chunks.\n3. **Synthesize**: answer with citations from retrieved context.\n4. **Act**: call tools via structured tool calling.\n5. **Checkpoint / Interrupt**: pause before irreversible actions.\n6. **Finalize**: produce user-facing response + structured metadata.\n\n## 3) RAG pipeline: make knowledge a first-class dependency\n\nRAG is the agent’s “read access” to reality:\n\n- chunk → embed → index\n- at query time: embed query → retrieve top-k → (optionally rerank) → generate\n\nKey production habit: treat retrieval as a component you can measure. Log:\n\n- retrieved doc IDs\n- similarity scores\n- whether the final answer actually used the retrieved text\n\n![Self-Ask: decomposes questions and queries external search (Adapted from Lilian Weng).](/api/wiki-images/agent-fundamentals/images/lilianweng-posts-2023-03-15-prompt-engineering_001.png)\n\n## 4) Tool use: structured calls, validated inputs\n\nTool calling is how your agent *does* things. The model proposes a function + arguments; your app executes it; the model then sees the result.\n\nDesign tools like APIs you’d be proud to ship:\n\n- small, single-purpose\n- explicit schemas\n- deterministic outputs\n- safe defaults\n\n## 5) Memory: separate “thread state” from “user memory”\n\nTwo kinds matter:\n\n- **Short-term (thread-scoped)**: the running conversation + intermediate artifacts (retrieved docs, tool results). Persist it with a checkpointer so you can resume after failures.\n- **Long-term (cross-thread)**: stable preferences and facts (“prefers concise answers”, “team = SRE”). Store it in a separate memory store and retrieve it when relevant.\n\nThis separation prevents your agent from dragging stale chat history into every prompt.\n\n## 6) Human-in-the-loop: interrupts before irreversible actions\n\nAny tool that changes the world (create ticket, send email, delete file) should go through a **checkpoint + approval** step.\n\nIn LangGraph terms: insert an **interrupt** node that surfaces the pending action and lets a human approve/modify/deny, then resume from the same state.\n\n## 7) Observability + evals: ship with headlights on\n\nProduction agents need:\n\n- **traces** (every LLM call, tool call, retrieved context)\n- **metrics** (latency, cost, tool error rate, retrieval quality)\n- **evals** (a small, representative set of tasks that catch regressions)\n\nA simple eval strategy:\n\n- golden Q&A pairs for RAG\n- “should call tool” vs “should not call tool” classification\n- LLM-as-judge rubric for open-ended quality (with bias awareness)\n\n## Minimal LangGraph skeleton (stateful + tools + RAG hooks)\n\n```python\nfrom typing_extensions import TypedDict\nfrom langgraph.graph import StateGraph, START, END\n\nclass State(TypedDict):\n    messages: list\n    retrieved: list\n    pending_action: dict | None\n\ndef route(state: State) -> str:\n    # Decide: \"rag\" | \"act\" | \"clarify\"\n    ...\n\ndef retrieve(state: State):\n    # Embed query -> vector search -> return chunks\n    return {\"retrieved\": [...]}\n\ndef answer(state: State):\n    # LLM uses state[\"retrieved\"] to answer with citations\n    return {\"messages\": state[\"messages\"] + [{\"role\": \"ai\", \"content\": \"...\"}]}\n\ndef act(state: State):\n    # Tool calling; set pending_action for approval if needed\n    return {\"pending_action\": {\"tool\": \"create_ticket\", \"args\": {...}}}\n\ndef approve(state: State) -> str:\n    # Human gate: \"approved\" | \"denied\"\n    ...\n\ng = StateGraph(State)\n\ng.add_node(\"retrieve\", retrieve)\n\ng.add_node(\"answer\", answer)\n\ng.add_node(\"act\", act)\n\ng.add_edge(START, \"retrieve\")\n\ng.add_conditional_edges(\"retrieve\", route, {\n    \"rag\": \"answer\",\n    \"act\": \"act\",\n    \"clarify\": \"answer\",\n})\n\ng.add_edge(\"answer\", END)\n\ngraph = g.compile()\n```\n\n## Summary\nA production-ready agent is an engineered system: a graph of decisions, retrieval, tool execution, memory, and checkpoints—not a single clever prompt. If you can trace it, measure it, and safely pause it, you can improve it.\n\n## Recommended Reading\n- [LangGraph: Agentic concepts](https://langchain-ai.github.io/langgraph/concepts/agentic_concepts/) — Patterns for building agents as graphs with durable execution.\n- [LangGraph: Memory](https://langchain-ai.github.io/langgraph/concepts/memory/) — Short-term vs long-term memory and how persistence works.\n- [A comprehensive guide for building RAG-based LLM applications](https://www.anyscale.com/blog/a-comprehensive-guide-for-building-rag-based-llm-applications-part-1) — Practical RAG pipeline design, scaling, and evaluation.\n- [Practical patterns for integrating LLMs into products](https://eugeneyan.com/writing/llm-patterns/) — Evals, guardrails, caching, and feedback loops for real systems.\n",
          "summary": "This capstone walks through designing an end-to-end production agent in LangGraph: graph-based orchestration, RAG for grounded knowledge, structured tool use, memory, human approval checkpoints, and observability with evals.",
